{"title_page": "MS The World", "text_new": "{{short description|Very large private residential yacht}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{| {{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=The World (in Melbourne).JPG\n| Ship caption=''The World'' in [[Melbourne, Victoria]], Australia\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship name=''The World''\n| Ship owner=\n| Ship operator= ROW Management, Ltd. [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], United States\n| Ship registry={{BHS}}c\n| Ship route=\n| Ship ordered=2000\n| Ship builder=[[Fosen Mekaniske Verksteder|Fosen Mek. Verksteder A/S]] in [[Rissa, Norway]]\n| Ship original cost=\n| Ship yard number=N.71\n| Ship way number=\n| Ship laid down=2001\n| Ship launched=28 February 2001\n| Ship completed=20 February 2002\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship acquired=\n| Ship maiden voyage=\n| Ship in service=\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|9219331}}\n*{{MMSI Number|311213000}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: C6RW4\n| Ship fate=\n| Ship status=In service\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class=\n| Ship tonnage={{GT|43,188}}\n| Ship displacement=\n| Ship length={{convert|196.35|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam={{convert|29.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height=\n| Ship draught=\n| Ship draft={{convert|6.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth=\n| Ship decks=12\n| Ship deck clearance=\n| Ship ramps=\n| Ship ice class=\n| Ship sail plan=\n| Ship power=Marine [[Diesel engine|diesel]]\n| Ship propulsion=\n| Ship speed={{convert|18.5|kn}}\n| Ship capacity=150-200 passengers average\n| Ship crew=280\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''The World''''' is the largest privately owned residential yacht. The residents, from about 45 countries, live on board as the ship travels, staying in most ports several days. Some residents choose to live on board full-time while others visit periodically throughout the year.<ref name=\"Hallman\" /> It is operated by ROW Management, Ltd., headquartered in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"aboardtheworld-contact\" />\n\nIt has 165 residences (106 apartments, 19 studio apartments, and 40 studios), all owned by the ship's residents. Average occupancy is 150\u2013200 residents and guests.\n\n''The World'' ([[IMO ship identification number]]: 9219331) flies the flag of [[The Bahamas]] and has a gross tonnage of 43,188 tons. It is {{convert|196.35|m|ftin}} long, {{convert|29.8|m|ft}} wide, and has a {{convert|6.7|m|ft|adj=on}} draft, 12 decks, and a maximum speed of {{convert|18.5|kn|km/h mph}}. The crew numbers approximately 280.\n\n{{As of|2017|January|28}} ''The World'' holds the world record for the southernmost ship voyage. The record was broken by her Capitan Dag H. Saevik, and the 63 residents on board at the time as well as crewmembers. The ship reached 78\u00b043\u2022997\u00b4S and 163\u00b041\u2022421\u00b4W at the [[Bay of Whales]] in Antarctica\u2019s [[Ross Sea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New record set for furthest south ship has ever sailed |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/morningreport/audio/201831446/new-record-set-for-furthest-south-ship-has-ever-sailed |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=RNZ |publisher=Radio New Zealand |date=31 January 2017 |ref=Rnz-south-most |language=en-nz}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020 the ship was emptied of passengers and non-essential crew because of concerns about the [[COVID-19]] pandemic. <ref>[https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/22620-the-world-residence-ship-also-lays-up.html Cruise Industry News: \"The World also lays up\" 17 March 2020]</ref>. A date for when the ship will resume service has not been announced <ref>https://aboardtheworld.com/event-updates-and-timeline/</ref>\n== Original concept and construction ==\n\n[[File:The world at port in Mackay 2006a.jpg|thumb|right|In [[Mackay, Queensland]] in 2006.]]\nThe ship was the idea of [[Knut Kloster|Knut U. Kloster]], whose family had a long history in the marine industry.<ref name=\"Hallman\" /> Her hull was built in [[Landskrona]], Sweden, by [[\u00d6resundsvarvet]], and it was then towed to Fosen Mekaniske Verksted in Rissa, Norway, for completion. The vessel was launched in March 2002 and purchased by its residents in October 2003.\n\nThe management company is responsible for operations and administration of the ship, including hiring the employees. The residents, through their elected board of directors and a network of committees, provide guidance to the management about the ship's itinerary, finances, and lifestyle.<ref name=\"Hallman\" />\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe ship has a large lobby, deli and grocery store, a boutique and showroom, fitness center, billiard room, golf simulator and putting greens, a full-sized tennis court, jogging track, a spa, swimming pool, and cocktail lounges.<ref name=\"Hallman\" />\n\nThere are six restaurants for dining that supplement the kitchens or kitchenettes in most of the residences.<ref name=\"Hallman\" /> For on-board entertainment there is a movie theater, library and music performances.<ref name=\"Hallman\" /> In addition to shore excursions, various classes have been offered on board.<ref name=\"Hallman\" /> ''The World'' provides internet access in each residence.\n\n== Northwest Passage transits ==\n\nSetting sail from [[Nome, Alaska]], U.S. on 18 August 2012 and reaching [[Nuuk]], Greenland on 12 September 2012, the ship became the largest passenger vessel at the time to transit the [[Northwest Passage]].<ref name=\"Nunatsiaq1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674the_world_gets_the_green_light_to_transit_the_northwest_passage/|title=The World gets green light to transit Northwest Passage|date=31 August 2012|accessdate=2 October 2012|work=nunatsiaqonline.ca|publisher=Nunatsiaq News - Nortext Publishing Corporation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014175410/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674the_world_gets_the_green_light_to_transit_the_northwest_passage/|archive-date=14 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Nunatsiaq2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674less_ice_makes_Nunavut_accessible_but_money_stays_at_home/|title=Shrinking ice makes Nunavut more accessible to cruise ships, but money stays on board|date=4 September 2012|accessdate=2 October 2012|work=nunatsiaqonline.ca|publisher=Nunatsiaq News - Nortext Publishing Corporation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014174139/http://www.nunatsiaqonline.ca/stories/article/65674less_ice_makes_Nunavut_accessible_but_money_stays_at_home/|archive-date=14 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The ship, carrying 481 passengers and crew, for 26 days and {{convert|4800|nmi|km}} at sea, followed in the path of Captain [[Roald Amundsen]], the first sailor to complete the journey in 1906.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGt4k8CWvy4|title=Northwest Passage with Raul Touzon|date=30 September 2012|via=YouTube}}</ref> In 2019, the ship traversed the Passage from east to west, becoming the 300th vessel to make the voyage, and the largest to do so in both directions.\n\n== COVID-19 ==\n\nIn March 2020 the ship unloaded all passengers and non-essential crew because of concern about COVID-19 infection.  <ref>[https://10daily.com.au/news/australia/a200410cnvxk/a-luxury-private-cruise-ship-is-making-star-shapes-off-was-coast-and-no-one-knows-why-20200410 10daily: \"Luxury private cruise ship is making star shapes off West Australia coast\" 14 April 2020]</ref><ref>[https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/22620-the-world-residence-ship-also-lays-up.html Cruise Industry News: \"The World also lays up\" 17 March 2020]</ref>. The company has not announced when it will resume service. <ref>https://aboardtheworld.com/event-updates-and-timeline/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Utopia (cruise ship)|''Utopia'' (cruise ship)]], a similar resident-owned vessel under construction\n* [[Seasteading]], the concept of creating permanent dwellings at sea\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Hallman\">\n{{cite journal\n| last = Hallman\n| first = J. C.\n| title = A House Is a Machine to Live In\n| date = October 2009\n| journal = [[The Believer (magazine)|The Believer]]\n| url = https://believermag.com/a-house-is-a-machine-to-live-in/\n| accessdate = 7 February 2011\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"aboardtheworld-contact\">\n{{cite web\n| publisher = ResidenSea\n| work = aboardtheworld.com\n| title = The World&nbsp;\u2014 Contact Us\n| url = http://www.aboardtheworld.com/contact/\n| accessdate = 7 February 2011\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|The World (ship, 2002)}}\n* {{official website|http://www.aboardtheworld.com/}}\n* [http://www.marinetraffic.com/ais/shipdetails.aspx?MMSI=311213000 ''The World'' at marinetraffic.com] including the current ship position via [[Automatic Identification System]] (AIS)\n* {{csr|register=MSI|id=9219331|shipname=The World |accessdate=26 November 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:The World}}\n[[Category:Companies based in Florida|ResidenSea]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:2001 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rissa, Norway]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Landskrona]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Very large private residential yacht}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{| {{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=The World (in Melbourne).JPG\n| Ship caption=''The World'' in [[Melbourne, Victoria]], Australia\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship name=''The World''\n| Ship owner=\n| Ship operator= ROW Management, Ltd. [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], United States\n| Ship registry={{BHS}}c\n| Ship route=\n| Ship ordered=2000\n| Ship builder=[[Fosen Mekaniske Verksteder|Fosen Mek. Verksteder A/S]] in [[Rissa, Norway]]\n| Ship original cost=\n| Ship yard number=N.71\n| Ship way number=\n| Ship laid down=2001\n| Ship launched=28 February 2001\n| Ship c